## Introduction

Every feature engineering method in Feature Forge implements `ArtifactExporter`, providing a uniform interface to scripts, DataFrames, and metadata. This notebook demonstrates artifact schemas, comparison, diff, and dashboard generation.

## Setup

::: {#setup .cell execution_count=1}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import os
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification

print("Artifacts & Dashboard Demo")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Artifacts & Dashboard Demo
```
:::
:::


## Load Data

::: {#load-data .cell cache='true' execution_count=2}
``` {.python .cell-code}
X, y = make_classification(
    n_samples=200, n_features=5, n_informative=3, random_state=42
)
df = pd.DataFrame(X, columns=[f"c{i+1}" for i in range(X.shape[1])])
df["target"] = y

X_train = df.drop(columns=["target"])
y_train = df["target"]
```
:::


## ArtifactConfig

::: {#artifact-config .cell execution_count=3}
``` {.python .cell-code}
from feature_forge.artifacts import ArtifactConfig

# In-memory mode (default)
mem_cfg = ArtifactConfig(storage_mode="memory")
print(f"Memory config: {mem_cfg}")

# Disk mode
disk_cfg = ArtifactConfig(storage_mode="disk", storage_format="parquet")
print(f"Disk config: {disk_cfg}")
```

